<subSubSection id="7FDF8CBDFF83FF95FF19103E23B8FC24" pageId="11" pageNumber="56" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="377ADF36FF83FF95FF19103E23B8FC24" blockId="11.[113,764,858,978]" pageId="11" pageNumber="56">
<emphasis id="05B10324FF83FF95FF19103E2044FC84" box="[151,281,858,882]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="56">Etymology. –</emphasis>
The epithet 
<taxonomicName id="F0C5A4B5FF83FF95FE15103E2344FC84" box="[411,537,858,882]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapindaceae" genus="Beguea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="11" pageNumber="56" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="birtinshaaeii">
<emphasis id="05B10324FF83FF95FE15103E2344FC84" box="[411,537,858,882]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="56">birkinshawii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
honors Chris Birkinshaw, who collected the type material while conducting his thesis work in the Lokobe reserve, and who has been an inspirational leader of plant conservation efforts in Madagascar.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="7FDF8CBDFF83FF95FF19109F21BAFB24" pageId="11" pageNumber="56" type="conservation">
<paragraph id="377ADF36FF83FF95FF19109F21BAFB24" blockId="11.[113,764,1018,1234]" pageId="11" pageNumber="56">
<emphasis id="05B10324FF83FF95FF19109F2035FBE4" box="[151,360,1019,1042]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="56">Conservation status</emphasis>
. – Despite the very restricted AOO within the well-protected Lokobe Special Reserve (
<figureCitation id="AFFEC3B3FF83FF95FD22177E23B2FBC4" box="[684,751,1050,1074]" captionStart="Fig. 4" captionStartId="6.[136,163,1315,1334]" captionTargetBox="[136,786,276,1300]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[136,786,276,1300]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 4. – Geographic distribution of Begueo opetolo Capuron (circles), B. birkinshowii G. E. Schatz, Gereau &amp; Lowry (stars), B. boreolis G. E. Schatz &amp; Lowry (diamond), B. tsorotononensis G. E. Schatz, Gereau &amp; Lowry (squares) and B. turkii G. E. Schatz, Gereau &amp; Lowry (triangles), mapped on the bioclimatic zones of Madagascar (after CORNET, 1974; see SCHATZ, 2000)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/888183/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="56">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
), there appear to be no current threats, and thus 
<taxonomicName id="F0C5A4B5FF83FF95FDEB175F21E8FB84" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapindaceae" genus="Beguea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="11" pageNumber="56" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="birtinshaaeii">
<emphasis id="05B10324FF83FF95FDEB175F21E8FB84" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="56">Beguea birkinshawii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is assigned a status of “Least Concern” [LC] using the IUCN Red List Criteria (
<bibRefCitation id="5354A2C7FF83FF95FE17171E2370FB64" author="IUCN" box="[409,557,1146,1170]" firstAuthor="IUCN" journalOrPublisher="IUCN Species Survival Commission, Gland &amp; Cambridge" pageId="11" pageNumber="56" refId="ref13043" refString="IUCN (2012). IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria: Version 3.1. 2 nd ed. IUCN Species Survival Commission, Gland &amp; Cambridge." title="IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria: Version 3.1. 2 nd ed." type="book" year="2012">IUCN, 2012</bibRefCitation>
), with the caution that this status is highly dependent on continued effective protection.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="7FDF8CBDFF83FF95FF19179F2310F9E4" pageId="11" pageNumber="56" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="377ADF36FF83FF95FF19179F2310F9E4" blockId="11.[113,764,1274,1554]" pageId="11" pageNumber="56">
<emphasis id="05B10324FF83FF95FF19179F218DFAE4" box="[151,208,1275,1298]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="56">Notes</emphasis>
. – 
<taxonomicName id="F0C5A4B5FF83FF95FF7C179F2095FAE4" box="[242,456,1274,1298]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapindaceae" genus="Beguea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="11" pageNumber="56" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="birtinshaaeii">
<emphasis id="05B10324FF83FF95FF7C179F2095FAE4" box="[242,456,1274,1298]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="56">Beguea birkinshawii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known only from subhumid forest in the Lokobe Special Reserve on the island of Nossi Be (
<figureCitation id="AFFEC3B3FF83FF95FF6D165E2079FAA4" box="[227,292,1338,1362]" captionStart="Fig. 4" captionStartId="6.[136,163,1315,1334]" captionTargetBox="[136,786,276,1300]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[136,786,276,1300]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 4. – Geographic distribution of Begueo opetolo Capuron (circles), B. birkinshowii G. E. Schatz, Gereau &amp; Lowry (stars), B. boreolis G. E. Schatz &amp; Lowry (diamond), B. tsorotononensis G. E. Schatz, Gereau &amp; Lowry (squares) and B. turkii G. E. Schatz, Gereau &amp; Lowry (triangles), mapped on the bioclimatic zones of Madagascar (after CORNET, 1974; see SCHATZ, 2000)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/888183/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="56">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). It can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="F0C5A4B5FF83FF95FDFA165F2390FAA4" box="[628,717,1338,1362]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapindaceae" genus="Beguea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="11" pageNumber="56" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="turtii">
<emphasis id="05B10324FF83FF95FDFA165F2390FAA4" box="[628,717,1338,1362]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="56">B. turkii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the species most similar morphologically, by its slender pedicels (0.2-0.5 mm in diam. in flower, 0.9-1 mm in diam. in fruit vs 0.7-0.9 mm in diam. in flower, 1.3-1.5 mm in diam. in fruit), smaller sepals (c. 0.5 mm vs c. 1.5 mm long), and smaller ellipsoid to obovoid fruit (1.7-1.8 cm long, c. 1.2 cm in diam vs globose fruit 2.3-2.8 cm in diam) (
<figureCitation id="AFFEC3B3FF83FF95FE71169E231DF9E4" box="[511,576,1530,1554]" captionStart="Fig. 7" captionStartId="10.[136,163,1905,1924]" captionTargetBox="[136,1454,276,1869]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[136,1454,276,1869]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Fig. 7. – Begueo birkinshowii G. E. Schatz, Gereau &amp; Lowry. A. Flowering branch; B. Detail of flower at anthesis; C. Portion of inflorescence axis. [Birkinshow 159, MO] [Drawing: R. L. Andriamiarisoa]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/888189/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="56">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
